Hi Nic,

Long story short, I now recall why Java is included in some of the NGINX/NodeJS and other MW images.

From previous discussions with the MW and NGC teams, Java isn't required by NGINX, NodeJS, or the other MW runtimes themselves. The dependency comes from the CyberArk NGC client, which is currently used for certificate and secret retrieval automation. NGC is Java-based and includes client-side cryptographic functionality, so Java becomes a dependency of the image.

The MW teams are trying to slim down their UBI9 Minimal/Micro images, but at the moment there doesn't appear to be a native alternative to NGC. The NGC team also indicated they don't currently have plans or capacity to develop one without a clear business case, requirements, and funding.

From a base image uplift perspective, this appears to be one of the key blockers preventing some MW images from becoming truly minimal.

Given that, do you think this is something we should simply accept as a current platform constraint, or is there enough value in image minimisation, CVE reduction, and standardisation to justify building a business case and engaging the relevant stakeholders?
